### Organize Commands Hierarchically with Route Maps

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Illustrates the use of `buildRouteMap` to create nested command structures and manage aliases. This function allows for organizing commands into logical groups, improving CLI navigation and offering shorthand command invocation.

```typescript
import { buildRouteMap, buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

// Helper function to create math commands
function buildUnaryMathCommand(op: "log" | "sqrt") {
    return buildCommand({
        func: (flags: {}, input: number) => {
            console.log(Math[op](input));
        },
        parameters: {
            positional: {
                kind: "tuple",
                parameters: [
                    {
                        brief: "Input number",
                        parse: numberParser,
                    },
                ],
            },
        },
        docs: {
            brief: `Run ${op} on input`,
        },
    });
}

// Create nested route map for math operations
const mathRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        log: buildUnaryMathCommand("log"),
        sqrt: buildUnaryMathCommand("sqrt"),
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Various math operations",
    },
});

// Create root route map with multiple commands
const rootRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        echo: echoCommand, // Assuming echoCommand is defined elsewhere
        math: mathRouteMap,
    },
    aliases: {
        e: "echo",  // Allow 'mycli e "hello"' as shorthand
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "All available commands",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli math sqrt 16  -> outputs 4
// Usage: mycli e "test"      -> outputs "test" (using alias)
```

--------------------------------

### Nested Command Definitions - nested/commands.ts

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/packages/create-app/tests/baselines/reference/app/creates new application/multi-command/commonjs/additional features/without auto-complete.txt

Defines nested commands ('foo' and 'bar') using `buildCommand` from `@stricli/core`. Each command has a loader function to import its implementation and defines its parameters and documentation. These commands are then grouped into a route map.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, buildRouteMap } from "@stricli/core";

export const fooCommand = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => {
        const { foo } = await import("./impl");
        return foo;
    },
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested foo command",
    },
});

export const barCommand = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => {
        const { bar } = await import("./impl");
        return bar;
    },
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested bar command",
    },
});

export const nestedRoutes = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        foo: fooCommand,
        bar: barCommand,
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested commands",
    },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Build Nested Route Map

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/command-routing/route-maps.mdx

Illustrates creating nested route maps where a route can itself be another route map. This allows for hierarchical command structures, organizing related sub-commands under a parent.

```typescript
/// commands.ts
const itemActionsRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
  routes: {
    create: createItemCommand,
    rename: renameItemCommand,
    delete: deleteItemCommand,
  },
  ...
});

const root = buildRouteMap({
  routes: {
    login: loginCommand,
    item: itemActionsRouteMap,
  },
  ...
});
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Route Map with Descriptions

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/command-routing/route-maps.mdx

Demonstrates how to build a route map using a TypeScript function. It includes setting a 'brief' description for commands and an optional 'fullDescription' for detailed help text, as well as a 'hideRoute' option. This configuration directly impacts how commands are displayed in the application's help output.

```typescript
buildRouteMap({
  docs: {
    brief: "This is a brief description of the routes",
    fullDescription: [
      "This is the full description of the routes.",
      "It should include all of the necessary details about the subcommands within.",
      "It will only be displayed to the user in the help text for this route.",
    ].join("\n"),
    hideRoute: {
      secret: true,
    },
  },
  ...
});
```

### Stricli - Type-Safe CLI Framework > Core APIs and Functions > buildRouteMap - Organize Commands Hierarchically

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Creates a route map that organizes multiple commands or nested route maps into a hierarchical structure. Supports aliases and default commands for flexible CLI navigation.

### Build Type-Safe Command with Parameters

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Demonstrates how to create a command using `buildCommand`. It defines type-safe flags and positional parameters, ensuring compile-time validation of function signatures and parameter usage. Includes parsing for numbers and string inputs.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

// Define flag types
type Flags = {
    readonly count?: number;
};

// Build command with type-safe parameters
export const echoCommand = buildCommand({
    func: (flags: Flags, text: string) => {
        const count = flags.count ?? 1;
        for (let i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
            console.log(text);
        }
    },
    parameters: {
        flags: {
            count: {
                brief: "Number of times to repeat the argument",
                kind: "parsed",
                parse: numberParser,
                optional: true,
            },
        },
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [
                {
                    brief: "Text to repeat",
                    parse: String,
                    placeholder: "text",
                },
            ],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Echo the first argument to the console",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli echo "hello"           -> outputs "hello"
// Usage: mycli echo "hello" --count 3 -> outputs "hello" three times
```

--------------------------------

### Build CLI Command with Enum Flag - TypeScript

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/argument-parsing/examples/default-flag.txt

Creates a CLI command using buildCommand from @stricli/core that accepts a lineEnding flag with enum values ('lf' or 'crlf'). The command writes output to stdout indicating which line ending was selected. The flag has a default value of 'lf' and includes documentation for CLI help text.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, type CommandContext } from "@stricli/core";

interface Flags {
  lineEnding: "lf" | "crlf";
}

export const root = buildCommand({
  func(this: CommandContext, { lineEnding }: Flags) {
    this.process.stdout.write(`Switched line ending to ${lineEnding}`);
  },
  parameters: {
    flags: {
      lineEnding: {
        kind: "enum",
        values: ["lf", "crlf"],
        brief: "Line ending characters",
        default: "lf",
      },
    },
  },
  docs: {
    brief: "Example for live playground with flag configured with default value",
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define Boolean Flag Parameters

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Demonstrates how to define boolean flags with automatic negation support using `@stricli/core`. Boolean flags default to `false` if not specified, and can be explicitly set or negated.

```typescript
import { buildCommand } from "@stricli/core";

type Flags = {
    readonly verbose?: boolean;
};

const command = buildCommand({
    func: (flags: Flags) => {
        if (flags.verbose) {
            console.log("Verbose mode enabled");
        }
        console.log("Executing command...");
    },
    parameters: {
        flags: {
            verbose: {
                kind: "boolean",
                brief: "Enable verbose output",
                optional: true,
            },
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Example command with boolean flag",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli command              -> verbose is false
// Usage: mycli command --verbose    -> verbose is true
// Usage: mycli command --no-verbose -> verbose is false (explicit negation)

```

--------------------------------

### Define Parsed Flag Parameters

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Explains the definition of custom-typed flags using parser functions for complex types such as numbers, host addresses, or custom objects. Includes examples using `numberParser` and `String`.

```typescript
import { numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

type Flags = {
    readonly port?: number;
    readonly host?: string;
};

const command = buildCommand({
    func: (flags: Flags) => {
        const port = flags.port ?? 3000;
        const host = flags.host ?? "localhost";
        console.log(`Server starting on ${host}:${port}`);
    },
    parameters: {
        flags: {
            port: {
                kind: "parsed",
                parse: numberParser,
                brief: "Port number to listen on",
                placeholder: "port",
                optional: true,
            },
            host: {
                kind: "parsed",
                parse: String,
                brief: "Host address to bind",
                placeholder: "host",
                optional: true,
            },
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Start development server",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli command                    -> localhost:3000
// Usage: mycli command --port 8080        -> localhost:8080
// Usage: mycli command --host 0.0.0.0 --port 80 -> 0.0.0.0:80

```

### Named Flags > Case Style

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/argument-parsing/flags.mdx

By default, Stricli will ensure that flag names are matched exactly. However, the [`scanner.caseStyle`](../configuration.mdx#scanner-case-style) configuration option allows you to specify `"allow-kebab-for-camel"`. This extends the argument scanner to allow kebab-case versions of camelCase flag names. For example, a flag that is normally passed as `--allowEdits` could also be passed as `--allow-edits`.

There is a separate configuration option [`documentation.caseStyle`](../configuration.mdx#display-case-style) that controls which case style is used when displaying help text and documentation. By default, the documentation option will reflect the scanner option, but this can be manually overridden.

