### Build Nested Route Map

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/command-routing/route-maps.mdx

Illustrates creating nested route maps where a route can itself be another route map. This allows for hierarchical command structures, organizing related sub-commands under a parent.

```typescript
/// commands.ts
const itemActionsRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
  routes: {
    create: createItemCommand,
    rename: renameItemCommand,
    delete: deleteItemCommand,
  },
  ...
});

const root = buildRouteMap({
  routes: {
    login: loginCommand,
    item: itemActionsRouteMap,
  },
  ...
});
```

--------------------------------

### Organize Commands Hierarchically with Route Maps

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Illustrates the use of `buildRouteMap` to create nested command structures and manage aliases. This function allows for organizing commands into logical groups, improving CLI navigation and offering shorthand command invocation.

```typescript
import { buildRouteMap, buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

// Helper function to create math commands
function buildUnaryMathCommand(op: "log" | "sqrt") {
    return buildCommand({
        func: (flags: {}, input: number) => {
            console.log(Math[op](input));
        },
        parameters: {
            positional: {
                kind: "tuple",
                parameters: [
                    {
                        brief: "Input number",
                        parse: numberParser,
                    },
                ],
            },
        },
        docs: {
            brief: `Run ${op} on input`,
        },
    });
}

// Create nested route map for math operations
const mathRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        log: buildUnaryMathCommand("log"),
        sqrt: buildUnaryMathCommand("sqrt"),
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Various math operations",
    },
});

// Create root route map with multiple commands
const rootRouteMap = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        echo: echoCommand, // Assuming echoCommand is defined elsewhere
        math: mathRouteMap,
    },
    aliases: {
        e: "echo",  // Allow 'mycli e "hello"' as shorthand
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "All available commands",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli math sqrt 16  -> outputs 4
// Usage: mycli e "test"      -> outputs "test" (using alias)
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Route Map with Descriptions

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/command-routing/route-maps.mdx

Demonstrates how to build a route map using a TypeScript function. It includes setting a 'brief' description for commands and an optional 'fullDescription' for detailed help text, as well as a 'hideRoute' option. This configuration directly impacts how commands are displayed in the application's help output.

```typescript
buildRouteMap({
  docs: {
    brief: "This is a brief description of the routes",
    fullDescription: [
      "This is the full description of the routes.",
      "It should include all of the necessary details about the subcommands within.",
      "It will only be displayed to the user in the help text for this route.",
    ].join("\n"),
    hideRoute: {
      secret: true,
    },
  },
  ...
});
```

--------------------------------

### Nested Command Definitions - nested/commands.ts

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/packages/create-app/tests/baselines/reference/app/creates new application/multi-command/commonjs/additional features/without auto-complete.txt

Defines nested commands ('foo' and 'bar') using `buildCommand` from `@stricli/core`. Each command has a loader function to import its implementation and defines its parameters and documentation. These commands are then grouped into a route map.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, buildRouteMap } from "@stricli/core";

export const fooCommand = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => {
        const { foo } = await import("./impl");
        return foo;
    },
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested foo command",
    },
});

export const barCommand = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => {
        const { bar } = await import("./impl");
        return bar;
    },
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested bar command",
    },
});

export const nestedRoutes = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        foo: fooCommand,
        bar: barCommand,
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Nested commands",
    },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Build Application with Route Mapping in TypeScript

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/packages/create-app/tests/baselines/reference/app/creates new application/multi-command/commonjs/package properties/custom name and bin command.txt

Initialize Stricli application with route mapping, command registration, and documentation configuration. Imports commands from subdirectories and sets up install/uninstall auto-completion commands. Exports application instance with name, version, and description metadata.

```typescript
import { buildApplication, buildRouteMap } from "@stricli/core";
import { buildInstallCommand, buildUninstallCommand } from "@stricli/auto-complete";
import { name, version, description } from "../package.json";
import { subdirCommand } from "./commands/subdir/command";
import { nestedRoutes } from "./commands/nested/commands";

const routes = buildRouteMap({
    routes: {
        subdir: subdirCommand,
        nested: nestedRoutes,
        install: buildInstallCommand("test-cli", { bash: "__test-cli_bash_complete" }),
        uninstall: buildUninstallCommand("test-cli", { bash: true }),
    },
    docs: {
        brief: description,
        hideRoute: {
            install: true,
            uninstall: true,
        },
    },
});

export const app = buildApplication(routes, {
    name,
    versionInfo: {
        currentVersion: version,
    },
});
```

