### Build Type-Safe Command with Parameters

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Demonstrates how to create a command using `buildCommand`. It defines type-safe flags and positional parameters, ensuring compile-time validation of function signatures and parameter usage. Includes parsing for numbers and string inputs.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";

// Define flag types
type Flags = {
    readonly count?: number;
};

// Build command with type-safe parameters
export const echoCommand = buildCommand({
    func: (flags: Flags, text: string) => {
        const count = flags.count ?? 1;
        for (let i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
            console.log(text);
        }
    },
    parameters: {
        flags: {
            count: {
                brief: "Number of times to repeat the argument",
                kind: "parsed",
                parse: numberParser,
                optional: true,
            },
        },
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [
                {
                    brief: "Text to repeat",
                    parse: String,
                    placeholder: "text",
                },
            ],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Echo the first argument to the console",
    },
});

// Usage: mycli echo "hello"           -> outputs "hello"
// Usage: mycli echo "hello" --count 3 -> outputs "hello" three times
```

--------------------------------

### Application Core Logic (app.ts)

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/packages/create-app/tests/baselines/reference/app/creates new application/single-command/commonjs/additional features/without auto-complete.txt

Builds the Stricli application by defining a command with positional and flag parameters. It imports necessary functions from '@stricli/core' and package metadata.

```typescript
import { buildApplication, buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";
import { name, version, description } from "../package.json";

const command = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => import("./impl"),
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [
                {
                    brief: "Your name",
                    parse: String,
                },
            ],
        },
        flags: {
            count: {
                kind: "parsed",
                brief: "Number of times to say hello",
                parse: numberParser,
            },
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: description,
    },
});

export const app = buildApplication(command, {
    name,
    versionInfo: {
        currentVersion: version,
    },
});

```

--------------------------------

### Build Command with Positional Arguments (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/argument-parsing/examples/placeholder-argument.txt

This snippet shows how to define a command using Stricli's buildCommand. It includes two positional parameters, 'src' for the source file and 'dest' for the destination path, both parsed as strings. The command's function writes a message to standard output indicating the file copy operation.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, type CommandContext } from "@stricli/core";

export const root = buildCommand({
  func(this: CommandContext, _: {}, src: string, dest: string) {
    this.process.stdout.write(`Copying file from ${src} to ${dest}`);
  },
  parameters: {
    positional: {
      kind: "tuple",
      parameters: [
        {
          brief: "Source file",
          parse: String,
          placeholder: "src",
        },
        {
          brief: "Destination path",
          parse: String,
          placeholder: "dest",
        },
      ],
    },
  },
  docs: {
    brief: "Example for live playground with positional arguments labeled by placeholders",
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Implement Lazy Command Loading in TypeScript

Source: https://context7.com/bloomberg/stricli/llms.txt

Optimize application startup time by deferring command module imports until execution. Uses an async loader function that dynamically imports the command module only when invoked. The loaded module must export a default async function matching the command signature.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, numberParser } from "@stricli/core";
import type { CommandModule } from "@stricli/core";

// Instead of importing directly, use loader
const heavyCommand = buildCommand({
    loader: async () => {
        // This import only happens when command is executed
        const module = await import("./commands/heavy-processing");
        return module.default;
    },
    parameters: {
        positional: {
            kind: "tuple",
            parameters: [
                {
                    brief: "Input file",
                    parse: String,
                },
            ],
        },
    },
    docs: {
        brief: "Process large data files",
    },
});

// The heavy-processing module structure:
// export default async function(flags: {}, inputFile: string): Promise<void | Error> {
//     // Heavy processing logic here
// }
```

--------------------------------

### Stricli CLI Command: Build File Move Functionality (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/bloomberg/stricli/blob/main/docs/docs/features/argument-parsing/examples/tuple-argument.txt

Defines a command-line command using Stricli's `buildCommand` function. It accepts two positional string parameters, 'from' and 'to', representing the origin and destination paths for a file. The command prints a message to standard output indicating the move operation. Dependencies include '@stricli/core'.

```typescript
import { buildCommand, type CommandContext } from "@stricli/core";

export const root = buildCommand({
  func(this: CommandContext, _: {}, from: string, to: string) {
    this.process.stdout.write(`Moving file from ${from} to ${to}`);
  },
  parameters: {
    positional: {
      kind: "tuple",
      parameters: [
        {
          brief: "Origin path",
          parse: String,
        },
        {
          brief: "Destination path",
          parse: String,
        },
      ],
    },
  },
  docs: {
    brief: "Example for live playground with positional parameters",
  },
});
```

